{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a568e980-7647-4bb8-8d0a-f5899226cbca","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_k8mVXy6fKQ71fpy46rBOjq","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with crashdump"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_ux7CXuSriI7VxceM1Azz3H","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-ac8d3d511eb24a9e89332e269d3f3759 && dotnet test --blame-crash 2>&1","description":"Run dotnet test with crash dump collection","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test with crash dump collection"}],"interactionId":"a4dcca87-0eb8-4957-aa75-7c6f7e4796e7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run these tests with `dotnet test` and collect a crash dump if any test crashes the host process. \n\nTo collect crash dumps when a .NET process crashes, you can use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variable (or `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump` for older runtimes). Setting this to `1` enables crash dump collection. You can also control the dump type and path with:\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` — 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` — path/pattern for the dump file\n\nSince this project uses the Microsoft Testing Platform with `dotnet test`, there's also the `--crashdump` option available (or `--blame-crash` for the older vstest approach). Given the setup with TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport enabled and the recent SDK/MSTest versions, the `--crashdump` flag would be the more direct way to capture dumps when tests crash. Since the testing platform bridge is active with that environment variable, `dotnet test --blame-crash` should translate the vstest syntax properly and work with the Microsoft Testing Platform. Let me just try running it to see if it works.","outputTokens":796,"requestId":"BD15:E210B:243C920:28E39A1:6A07E25E"},"id":"6f78f95e-7c4c-4e6d-8a88-24f6b116600f","timestamp":"2026-05-16T03:20:13.414Z","parentId":"7203f175-3aa3-4eed-8438-bbcb2dba